To nurture virtue in a corrupt society, and to conceal one's benevolence;
Born in a country, to educate its people as the purifying element;
Caring for one's hometown,
Teaching as a master in a humble setting, amidst the rustic landscape;
Shepherding the common folk,
If one uses machinery to manage forests, tranquility will be lost;
Unenlightened, one has not yet grasped the meaning;
Once one's name becomes a beacon of righteousness,
Friendships blossom in the secluded wilderness.
Once a monarch embraces the Way,
His rule transforms the nation,
And justice becomes the guiding moon.

This poem emphasizes the role of benevolent individuals in a corrupt society. The poet describes how such individuals, despite the prevailing moral decay, dedicate themselves to nurturing virtue and educating the people. They find solace in rural settings, away from the marketplace, and dedicate themselves to shepherding the common folk. The metaphor of a moon guiding a nation underscores the transformative power of righteous rule. The poem also touches upon the importance of education and the potential dangers of relying on machinery to manage natural resources. Ultimately, the poet asserts that the foundation of a virtuous society lies in the actions and intentions of its leaders.
